collections.collection_description: Climate variables for current climate conditions in Australia, with adjustment for the radiative effects of terrain.

datasets.title: Australia, current climate BIOCLIM variable suite (1976-2005), 9 arcsec (~250 m)
datasets.description: BIOCLIM variable suite of current climate variables for Australia.
datasets.description_full: A suite of 9s resolution BIOCLIM climate surfaces for the Australian continent. This collection represents a 30 year average centred on 1990 for 19 variables from the standard set of 35 BIOCLIM variables.
datasets.citation: Harwood, Tom (2019): 9s climatology for continental Australia 1976-2005: BIOCLIM variable suite. v1. CSIRO. Data Collection.https://doi.org/10.25919/5dce30cad79a8

layers.title: Bioclim 01: Annual mean temperature
layers.tooltip: The annual mean temperature approximates the total energy inputs for an ecosystem.

layers.title: Bioclim 02: Mean Diurnal Range (Mean of monthly (max temp - min temp))
layers.tooltip: This index can help provide information pertaining to the relevance of temperature fluctuation for different species.

layers.title: Bioclim 03: Isothermality (BIO2/BIO7) (* 100)
layers.tooltip: Isothermality quantifies how large the day-to-night temperatures oscillate relative to the summer- to-winter (annual) oscillations. An isothermal value of 100 indicates the diurnal temperature range is equiva- lent to the annual temperature range, while anything less than 100 indicates a smaller level of temperature variability within an average month relative to the year. A species distribution may be influenced by larger or smaller temperature fluctuations within a month relative to the year and this predictor is useful for ascertaining such information.

layers.title: Bioclim 04: Temperature Seasonality (standard deviation *100)
layers.tooltip: Temperature seasonality is a measure of temperature change over the course of the year. The larger the value, the greater the variability of temperature.

layers.title: Bioclim 05: Max Temperature of Warmest Month
layers.tooltip: This information is useful when examining whether species distributions are affected by warm temperature anomalies throughout the year.

layers.title: Bioclim 06: Min Temperature of Coldest Month
layers.tooltip: This information is useful when examining whether species distributions are affected by cold temperature anomalies throughout the year.

layers.title: Bioclim 07: Temperature Annual Range (BIO5-BIO6)
layers.tooltip: This information is useful when examining whether species distributions are affected by ranges of extreme temperature conditions.

layers.title: Bioclim 08: Mean Temperature of Wettest Quarter
layers.tooltip: This index provides mean temperatures during the wettest three months of the year, which can be useful for examining how such environmental factors may affect species seasonal distributions

layers.title: Bioclim 09: Mean Temperature of Driest Quarter
layers.tooltip: This index provides mean temperatures during the driest three months of the year, which can be useful for examining how such environmental factors may affect species seasonal distributions

layers.title: Bioclim 10: Mean Temperature of Warmest Quarter
layers.tooltip: This index provides mean temperatures during the warmest three months of the year, which can be useful for examining how such environmental factors may affect species seasonal distributions.

layers.title: Bioclim 11: Mean Temperature of Coldest Quarter
layers.tooltip: This index provides mean temperatures during the coldest three months of the year, which can be useful for examining how such environmental factors may affect species seasonal distributions.

layers.title: Bioclim 12: Annual Precipitation
layers.tooltip: Annual total precipitation approximates the total water inputs and is therefore useful when ascertaining the importance of water availability to a species distribution.

layers.title: Bioclim 13: Precipitation of Wettest Month
layers.tooltip: The wettest month is useful if extreme precipitation conditions during the year influence a species potential range.

layers.title: Bioclim 14: Precipitation of Driest Month
layers.tooltip: The driest month is useful if extreme precipitation conditions during the year influence a species potential range.

layers.title: Bioclim 15: Precipitation Seasonality (Coefficient of Variation)
layers.tooltip: Since species distributions can be strongly influenced by variability in precipitation, this index provides a percentage of precipitation variability where larger percentages represent greater variability of precipitation.

layers.title: Bioclim 16: Precipitation of Wettest Quarter
layers.tooltip: This index provides total precipitation during the wettest three months of the year, which can be useful for examining how such environmental factors may affect species seasonal distributions.

layers.title: Bioclim 17: Precipitation of Driest Quarter
layers.tooltip: This index provides total precipitation during the driest three months of the year, which can be useful for examining how such environmental factors may affect species seasonal distributions.

layers.title: Bioclim 18: Precipitation of Warmest Quarter
layers.tooltip: This index provides total precipitation during the warmest three months of the year, which can be useful for examining how such environmental factors may affect species seasonal distributions.

layers.title: Bioclim 19: Precipitation of Coldest Quarter
layers.tooltip: This index provides total precipitation during the coldest three months of the year, which can be useful for examining how such environmental factors may affect species seasonal distributions.

datasets.title: Australia, current climate (1976-2005), CSIRO, 9 arcsec (~250 m)
datasets.description: 9s climatology for continental Australia 1976-2005: Summary variables with elevation and radiative adjustment
datasets.description_full: A suite of 9s resolution climate surfaces for the Australian continent, with adjustment for the radiative effects of terrain. This collection represents a 30 year average centred on 1990. Precipitation, temperature, evaporation and water balance data are presented as annual means or totals and maximum and minimum monthly values.

CSIRO. Data Collection. https://doi.org/10.4225/08/5afa9f7d1a552

collections.collection_description: Topography indices identifying areas of high flat areas or deposited material in flat valley bottoms in Australia.
collections.dataset collection_layers: Multi-resolution Ridge Top Flatness, Multi-resolution Valley Bottom Flatness

datasets.title: Multi-resolution Ridge Top Flatness (MrRTF)
datasets.description: A topographic index designed to identify high flat areas at a range of scales.
datasets.description_full: MrRTF is a topographic index designed to identify high flat areas at a range of scales. It complements the MrVBF index that is designed to identify areas of deposited material in flat valley bottoms. Unlike MrVBF, the MrRTF index does not have a clear link to landform processes but it has been found to be a useful adjunct to MrVBF in landform classification. Zero values indicate areas that are steep or low, with values 1 and larger indicating progressively larger areas of high flat land.
datasets.citation: Gallant, John; Dowling, Trevor; Austin, Jenet (2013): Multi-resolution Ridge Top Flatness (MrRTF). v2. CSIRO. Data Collection. https://doi.org/10.4225/08/56EA312A5E63B

layers.title: Multi-resolution Ridge Top Flatness (MrRTF)
layers.tooltip: This topographic index designed to identify high flat areas at a range of scales. Zero values indicate areas that are steep or low, with values 1 and larger indicating progressively larger areas of high flat land.

datasets.title: Multi-resolution Valley Bottom Flatness (MrVBF)
datasets.description: A topographic index designed to identify areas of deposited material at a range of scales.
datasets.description_full: MrVBF is a topographic index designed to identify areas of deposited material at a range of scales based on the observations that valley bottoms are low and flat relative to their surroundings and that large valley bottoms are flatter than smaller ones. Zero values indicate erosional terrain with values 1 and larger indicating progressively larger areas of deposition. There is some evidence that MrVBF values correlate with depth of deposited material.
datasets.citation: Gallant, John; Dowling, Trevor; Austin, Jenet (2012): Multi-resolution Valley Bottom Flatness (MrVBF). v3. CSIRO. Data Collection. https://doi.org/10.4225/08/5701C885AB4FE

layers.title: Multi-resolution Valley Bottom Flatness (MrVBF)
layers.tooltip: MrVBF is a topographic index is designed to identify areas of deposited material at a range of scales. Zero values indicate erosional terrain with values 1 and larger indicating progressively larger areas of deposition.

collections.collection_description: A suite of variables describing the geological conditions of the land surface in Australia.
collections.dataset collection_layers: Magnetic anomalies, Weathering intensity index, Range in geological age

datasets.title: Australia, substrate, CSIRO, 9 arcsec (~250 m)
datasets.description: Edaphic (physical and chemical conditions of the soil) and land surface physiography (landform and geomorphology) layers.
datasets.description_full: These data provide consistent rasterised layers of edaphic (physical and chemical conditions of the soil) and land surface physiography (landform and geomorphology) variables hypothesised to explain spatial patterns in biological diversity at continental scales for immediate use with statistical modelling tools. These data are intended to be used along with a similarly compiled and spatially standardised set of climatic layers. Consistent stacks of raster variables are needed for spatially-explicit biodiversity modelling using tools such as MAXENT or Generalised Dissimilarity Modelling (GDM). Full details of each dataset, with a list of data sources and bibliography, are provided in a table as part of the data collection.
datasets.citation: CSIRO; Williams, Kristen; Wilson, Peter; Viscarra Rossel, Raphael; Gallant, John; Austin, Jenet; Dowling, Trevor; Wilford, John; Chen, Charlie; McKenzie, Neil; De Vries, Robert; Jacquier, David; Storey, Randal (2013): 9 second substrate rasters for continental modelling of Australia's biodiversity patterns. v3. CSIRO. Data Collection. https://doi.org/10.25919/5bd6780e2fbc6

layers.title: Mean geological age
layers.tooltip: Mean geological age (millions of years before present) derived from the 1:1 million surface geology of Australia (Raymond 2009) by combining the descriptive geological age fields with the timescales database (Laurie et al. 2008) to assign numerical ages to each map unit.

layers.title: Range in geological ages
layers.tooltip: The range in age can help provide information pertaining to the substrate for different species and is derived as the difference between the minimum and maximum of the age values.

layers.title: Onshore gravity grid of Australia
layers.tooltip: The onshore gravity grid of Australia is a compilation of over 1.4 Million gravity stations using Bouguer gravity anomalies in galileo units of acceleration (Gal).

layers.title: Magnetics
layers.tooltip: These data derive from the 1000m gridded Magnetic Anomaly Map of Australia. The grid was compiled from about 9 million line-kilometres of TMI data held in the National Airborne Geophysics Database.

layers.title: Weathering intensity index
layers.tooltip: This weathering intensity index (WII) over the Australian continent has been developed at a 100m resolution using regression models based on airborne gamma-ray spectrometry imagery and the Shuttle Radar Topography Mission (SRTM) elevation data.

datasets.title: Australia, soil and landform, CSIRO, 9 arcsec (~250 m)
datasets.description: A selection of 9-arcsecond resolution substrate surfaces (soil and landform)
datasets.description_full: A selection of 9-arcsecond resolution substrate surfaces (soil and landform) for the Australian continent, aggregated from 3-arcsecond source data. the 9-arcsecond aggregated soil properties are spatially aggregated versions of the 3-arcsecond Soil and Landscape Grid of Australia (SLGA) soil attributes, aligned with the 9-arcsecond DEM of Australia. Each soil attribute is represented as three grids for each depth layer, giving the 5th, 50th and 95th percentile values.
datasets.citation: Gallant, John; Austin, Jenet; Williams, Kristen; Harwood, Tom; King, Darran; Nolan, Martin; Mokany, Karel (2018): 9s soil and landform for  continental Australia analysis of biodiversity pattern: aggregated from 3s data. v1. CSIRO. Data Collection. https://doi.org/10.4225/08/5b285fd14991f

layers.title: Topographic wetness index
layers.tooltip: Topographic Wetness Index estimates the relative wetness within a catchment.

layers.title: Slope
layers.tooltip: This index measures the inclination of the land surface from the horizontal.

layers.title: Profile curvature
layers.tooltip: This index is the rate of change of potential gradient down a flow line and represents the changes in flow velocity down a slope. It is significant for flow acceleration, erosion/deposition rates and geomorphology.

layers.title: Plan curvature
layers.tooltip: Plan (or contour) curvature is the rate of change of aspect (orthogonal to the slope) and represents topographic convergence or divergence. It is significant for water movement across the landscape.

layers.title: Elevation
layers.tooltip: This index can help provide information pertaining to the relevance of elevation change for different species.

layers.title: Contributing area
layers.tooltip: Contributing area is the contributing area in m2 computed using multiple flow directions on hillslopes and ANUDEM-derived flow directions in channels.

layers.title: Available Water Capacity
layers.tooltip: This index can help provide information pertaining to the relevance of available water capacity for different species.

layers.title: Bulk Density - Whole Earth
layers.tooltip: Bulk density of the whole soil (including coarse fragments) in mass per unit volume and is a useful indication of a soils physical condition.

layers.title: Clay
layers.tooltip: Clay is a useful proxy for defining the nutritional and biological capacity of soil.

layers.title: Depth of Regolith
layers.tooltip: Depth to hard rock, inclusive of all regolith.

layers.title: Depth of Soil
layers.tooltip: Depth of soil profile (A & B horizons)

layers.title: Effective Cation Exchange Capacity
layers.tooltip: This index can help provide information pertaining to the relevance of soil for difference species.

layers.title: Total Nitrogen
layers.tooltip: This index can help provide information pertaining to the relevance of soil chemistry for difference species.

layers.title: pH - CaCl2
